<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-699-680  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 699 680.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Sept 25 1989 n334 p38(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>U.S.S.R. gets PCs. (Phoenix Group International wins Sovietmicrocomputer contract)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hubbard, Holly.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A relatively small US technology firm, Phoenix GroupInternational, has been awarded a $1.2 million contract to providethe Soviet Union government with 6 million microcomputers.andP;  Thecontract will provide 3 million IBM-standard microcomputers toSoviet schools and universities, as well as 10 disklessworkstations that will be networked to an instructor's computerand a file server.andP;  Another 3 million microcomputers will bedistributed for resale outside the school system.andP;  All thecomputers were specifically designed in accordance with Sovietrequirements, manufactured by Netcom, a company Phoenix Groupacquired in 1988.andP;  Phoenix Group took partial payment in hardcurrency from the Soviets, and some in counter-trade, a commonpractice in third-world countries.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Phoenix Group International Inc. (contracts).andO;Topic:     Soviet UnionEducationGovernment ContractsMicrocomputersNetworks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>